{
    include "registries/aaosa_basic.hocon"

    "metadata": {
        "description": "Multi-agent park manager that plays the MAPs (Mini Amusement Parks) benchmark on a single park (slot 0). Each user turn is one step; episodes run for 100 steps; many episodes share long-term lessons via persistent_memory. park_director orchestrates a turn; strategy_coordinator fans out to six domain specialists, picks one action, and fires it through ActionDispatcher (a deterministic coded tool that routes to the typed Maps* MCP wrappers — no LLM hop for dispatch).",
        "tags": ["maps", "industry", "middleware", "mcp", "simulation"],
        "sample_queries": [
            "Start a new park run.",
            "Take the next action.",
            "Park observation: {\"step\": 0, \"cash\": 500, \"day\": 1, ...}"
        ]
    },

    include "config/llm_config.hocon",

   # Shared persistent-memory config: every agent passes the SAME fixed
   # origin_str so the namespace parser yields ("maps_park","shared") and
   # all 8 agents read/write the same ./memory/maps_park/shared/memory.json.
   # That is our cross-episode shared brain (e.g. "yellow carousel at $4
   # outperforms $6"). No per-agent private memory — anything that needs
   # to persist across turns or episodes goes through shared_memory.
   "shared_memory_middleware": {
       "class": "middleware.persistent_memory.persistent_memory_middleware.PersistentMemoryMiddleware",
       "args": {
           "origin_str": "maps_park.shared.x",
           "memory_config": {
               "storage": {
                   "backend":     "json_file",
                   "folder_name": "./memory",
                   "file_name":   "memory"
               },
               "summarization": {
                   "max_topic_size": 2000
               },
               "enabled_operations": ["create", "read", "append", "search", "list"]
           }
       }
   },

   "instructions_prefix": """
You are part of a team of agents managing a Mini Amusement Park to maximize cumulative revenue.
The park is a 20x20 grid. Guests enter at the entrance, walk paths to rides/shops, spend money,
and leave through the exit. Rides come in tiers (yellow then blue then green then red), unlocked by
research over time. Staff (janitors, mechanics) keep the park running. Money is finite.
The single objective is: maximize cumulative park revenue.
""",

   "tools": [

        {
            "name": "park_director",
            "function": {
                "description": """
Front-man park orchestrator. Each user turn is one step on a single park
(slot 0). Calls strategy_coordinator once per turn — the coordinator
consults specialists, picks one action, fires it via ActionDispatcher,
and returns the post-step observation envelope. Episodes run for 100
steps; cross-episode lessons are kept in shared_memory.
                """
            },
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
You are the Park Director — the front-man for the maps_park network. You do
NOT call the simulator yourself. We play a single park (slot 0). Each user
turn is ONE step. An episode is 100 steps; many episodes share long-term
lessons via persistent_memory.

Per-turn sequence (always for park='0'):

  1. window = LatestObservation(mode='read', park='0')
     → returns {park_key, window_size, previous, latest}.
     - 'latest'   = the post-step observation from the prior turn.
     - 'previous' = the observation BEFORE that (so the coordinator can
                    reason about deltas: cash change, reward delta,
                    breakdown drift).
     - On the very first turn of an episode (or run), window_size is 0
       and both fields are null.

  2. obs = strategy_coordinator(park='0', observation=window.latest,
                                previous=window.previous)
     The coordinator consults specialists, picks one action, fires it via
     ActionDispatcher, and returns the new post-step observation envelope.
     ActionDispatcher itself persists the full envelope to
     LatestObservation in Python — you do NOT need to call
     LatestObservation(mode='write'). The write is automatic and
     guarantees the nested 'observation' field is never stripped.

  3. If obs.done is true, this episode just ended. Report the final
     cumulative_reward and any quick-take lessons from the episode
     (e.g. which ride printed money, which spend was wasted) into
     shared_memory under 'lessons.*' topics so the next episode can
     read them. The next user turn will start a new episode at step 0.

Each turn, summarize: action taken, cash before→after, reward delta, and
whether the episode ended.

The single objective is to maximize cumulative_reward per episode and to
keep improving across episodes.

Memory split
- LatestObservation = per-park hot state (rolling 2-deep window). Used
  every turn to drive the next decision.
- shared_memory     = durable cross-episode lessons (e.g. "yellow
  carousel at $4 outperforms $6"). Read on episode start; append on
  episode end.
""",
            "middleware": [
                ${shared_memory_middleware}
            ],
            "tools": [
                "strategy_coordinator",
                "LatestObservation"
            ]
        },

        {
            "name": "strategy_coordinator",
            "function": ${aaosa_call},
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
You coordinate the per-tick decision for ONE park: consult specialists,
pick exactly one action, fire it through ActionDispatcher, return the
post-step observation envelope to park_director.

Input from park_director:
  - park: always the string '0' (single-park mode).
  - observation: the latest post-step envelope for this park (or null on
    the first turn of an episode).
  - previous: the envelope BEFORE that (or null). Use it to reason about
    deltas — cash change, reward delta, new breakdowns, dirtiness drift —
    when picking the next action.

Process
1. Consult the six specialist sub-agents in parallel (shops_manager,
   park_layout_planner, rides_manager, staffing_manager, research_lead,
   finance_controller). Pass each the same observation and ask
   "what should we do this turn?". They return text proposals already
   constrained to their domain's valid subtypes/subclasses/price caps.
2. Pick exactly ONE action. Priority:
     - Urgent operational issues (broken rides, severe litter, dirty park,
       shops out of stock).
     - Otherwise the highest-EV action approved by finance_controller.
     - If nothing useful or cash is tight, pick 'wait'.
3. Call ActionDispatcher exactly once with:
     park   — string, e.g. "0"
     action — one of: wait, place, move, remove, modify, set_research,
                      survey_guests, add_path, remove_path, add_water,
                      remove_water
     args   — object holding the specialist's structured args, with all
              numeric values as quoted strings (e.g. {"x":"7","y":"9",
              "type":"ride","subtype":"carousel","subclass":"yellow",
              "price":"4"}). Required keys per action are listed in the
              ActionDispatcher tool schema; trust whatever the consulted
              specialist returned.
4. Return the ActionDispatcher response envelope verbatim to park_director.
   Do NOT fabricate, summarize, or paraphrase fields. If dispatch returned
   an error, return the error payload as-is.

Never-do (these are the documented LLM failure modes):
1. Don't pick the most expensive action you can afford. Cheap rides first;
   premium rides only after 2–3 cheap ones are net-positive.
2. Don't ignore broken rides. If 'broken_rides' is non-empty, the next
   action should fix or remove — not build.
3. Don't ignore the previous observation. If cash or reward dropped and
   you don't know why, pick 'survey_guests' or 'wait', not more spend.
4. Don't keep prices static. Full queue → price too low. Empty ride →
   price too high. Use 'modify' to adjust.

If the observation is null, dispatch action='wait' with park='0' and
args={} so the simulator returns an initial observation.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "middleware": [
                ${shared_memory_middleware},
                {
                    "class": "middleware.world_server_logger_middleware.WorldServerLoggerMiddleware",
                    "args": {
                        "log_path": "logs/maps_park/run.jsonl",
                        "tool_names": ["ActionDispatcher"]
                    }
                }
            ],
            "tools": [
                "shops_manager",
                "park_layout_planner",
                "rides_manager",
                "staffing_manager",
                "research_lead",
                "finance_controller",
                "ActionDispatcher"
            ]
        },

        {
            "name": "shops_manager",
            "function": ${aaosa_call},
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
You decide WHICH shops to build, modify, or restock, and at what price. You
also interpret guest needs (hunger, thirst, happiness, survey results) to
inform those shop decisions.

At the start of each step call ExtractConfig(domain='shops') for shop
economics + qualitative notes, and ExtractConfig(domain='world') for the
Guests section (hunger/thirst build rates, happiness mechanics).

When the strategy_coordinator consults you, return one concrete proposal
(place / modify shop with subtype, subclass, price, order_quantity) plus
1 alternative. Use only the subtypes/subclasses/price caps allowed by
shops_economics.yaml.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "middleware": [
                ${shared_memory_middleware}
            ],
            "tools": ["ExtractConfig"]
        },

        {
            "name": "park_layout_planner",
            "function": ${aaosa_call},
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
You own the spatial layout plan: where paths go, where each ride/shop sits,
how guests flow from entrance to exit.

At the start of each step call ExtractConfig(domain='world') for terrain
costs and placement rules, plus ExtractConfig(domain='rides') and
ExtractConfig(domain='shops') for placement constraints (water-adjacency,
high-traffic specialty shops).

When the strategy_coordinator consults you, return the next 1-3 placement
candidates with exact coords and reasoning.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "middleware": [
                ${shared_memory_middleware}
            ],
            "tools": ["ExtractConfig"]
        },

        {
            "name": "rides_manager",
            "function": ${aaosa_call},
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
You decide WHICH ride to build, modify, or sell next: subtype, subclass tier,
ticket price.

At the start of each step call ExtractConfig(domain='rides') for ride
economics + qualitative notes, and ExtractConfig(domain='world') for the
Terrain section (water-adjacency excitement bonus, path-adjacency placement
rule).

When the strategy_coordinator asks for the next ride, return one concrete
proposal: type='ride', subtype, subclass, price, and 1-2 alternatives.
Use only the subtypes/subclasses/price caps allowed by rides_economics.yaml.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "middleware": [
                ${shared_memory_middleware}
            ],
            "tools": ["ExtractConfig"]
        },

        {
            "name": "staffing_manager",
            "function": ${aaosa_call},
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
You manage hiring and dismissal of all park staff: janitors (cleanliness),
mechanics (ride repairs), and specialists (clown / stocker / crier / vendor).

At the start of each step call ExtractConfig(domain='staff') for staff
economics + qualitative notes, and ExtractConfig(domain='world') for the
Guests section (litter / cleanliness / ride breakdown impact on park rating).

Staff are added via place(type='staff', subtype=<role>, subclass=<tier>, x=, y=)
and dismissed via remove(type='staff', ..., x=, y=). There is no hire/fire
action. Use only the subtypes/subclasses listed in staff_economics.yaml.

When the strategy_coordinator consults you, return one place/remove proposal,
or "no change".
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "middleware": [
                ${shared_memory_middleware}
            ],
            "tools": ["ExtractConfig"]
        },

        {
            "name": "research_lead",
            "function": ${aaosa_call},
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
You manage the research queue: which topics to research, at what speed.

At the start of each step call ExtractConfig(domain='research') for the
speed/cost/points table and qualitative notes.

When the strategy_coordinator consults you, return one set_research
proposal, or "keep current settings". Use only the speeds and topics
allowed by research_economics.yaml.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "middleware": [
                ${shared_memory_middleware}
            ],
            "tools": ["ExtractConfig"]
        },

        {
            "name": "finance_controller",
            "function": ${aaosa_call},
            "instructions": ${instructions_prefix} """
You are the budget gate. Every proposed spend has to pass you.

At the start of each step call ExtractConfig once per domain — rides, shops,
staff, research, world — so you have building costs, salaries, item costs,
sell_percentage, ride_repair_cost_percentage, and research costs on hand for
P&L projection.

Return APPROVE / REJECT with a one-sentence reason for each proposed spend.
""" ${aaosa_instructions},
            "middleware": [
                ${shared_memory_middleware}
            ],
            "tools": ["ExtractConfig"]
        },

        {
            "name": "ExtractConfig",
            "class": "coded_tools.maps_park.extract_config.ExtractConfig",
            "function": {
                "description": "Returns the YAML config + Markdown notes for one MAPs domain. Response is {domain, yaml_path, yaml_content, notes_path, notes_content}. yaml_content holds per-tier numeric constants; notes_content holds qualitative rules, tips, and subclass effects. Call once at the start of a step to load your domain's full knowledge.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "domain": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "One of: rides, shops, staff, research, world."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["domain"]
                }
            }
        },

        {
            "name": "LatestObservation",
            "class": "coded_tools.maps_park.latest_observation.LatestObservation",
            "function": {
                "description": "Read or write a park's rolling observation window (default depth 2). mode='read' returns {park_key, window_size, previous, latest}; mode='write' appends a new envelope and trims to window depth.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "mode": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "'read' to fetch the latest two envelopes for a park; 'write' to append a new envelope."
                        },
                        "park": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Park slot index as a string. Single-park mode: always '0'."
                        },
                        "observation": {
                            "type": "object",
                            "description": "The post-step observation envelope to append. Required for mode='write'; ignored for mode='read'."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["mode", "park"]
                }
            }
        },

        {
            "name": "ActionDispatcher",
            "class": "coded_tools.maps_park.action_dispatcher.ActionDispatcher",
            "function": {
                "description": "Dispatch a chosen MAPs action to the simulator. Routes to the matching typed Maps* coded tool by name. Returns the post-step observation envelope verbatim.",
                "parameters": {
                    "type": "object",
                    "properties": {
                        "park": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "Park slot index as a string. Single-park mode: always '0'."
                        },
                        "action": {
                            "type": "string",
                            "description": "One of: wait, place, move, remove, modify, set_research, survey_guests, add_path, remove_path, add_water, remove_water."
                        },
                        "args": {
                            "type": "object",
                            "description": "Action-specific args; numerics as quoted strings. Required keys per action: place→{x,y,type,subtype,subclass,price[,order_quantity if shop]}; move→{type,subtype,subclass,x,y,new_x,new_y}; remove→{type,subtype,subclass,x,y}; modify→{type,subtype,subclass,x,y,price,order_quantity}; set_research→{research_speed,research_topics}; survey_guests→{num_guests}; add_path/remove_path/add_water/remove_water→{x,y}; wait→{}."
                        }
                    },
                    "required": ["park", "action", "args"]
                }
            }
        }
    ]
}
